# Testing

## Tooling
- JUnit 5, AssertJ, Mockito (all from `spring-boot-starter-test`).
- H2 (in-memory) for `@DataJpaTest` and `@SpringBootTest` slices when speed matters.
- Testcontainers Postgres only if a slice cannot run on H2 (e.g. uses Postgres-specific JSONB or `@SQLRestriction` SQL that differs). Document the choice in the test class JavaDoc.

## Where tests live
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/<feature>/<ClassUnderTest>Test.java` — unit tests with Mockito.
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/<feature>/<Controller>WebMvcTest.java` — `@WebMvcTest` slice tests, mocking the service.
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/<feature>/<Repository>JpaTest.java` — `@DataJpaTest`.
- `src/test/java/com/att/tdp/issueflow/IssueFlowApplicationTests.java` — boot smoke test (already exists).
- `src/test/resources/application.yaml` — H2 datasource for tests.

## Naming
- `@DisplayName` per method describing the behavior, not the method name.
- Method pattern: `should<Behavior>_when<Condition>()`.
- Example: `should_return409_whenStatusTransitionIsBackward()`.

## What to cover (per slice — non-negotiable)
- Every service method with branching logic: one test per branch (happy path, each error path, each FSM transition).
- Every controller: at least one happy-path `@WebMvcTest` and one error-path test per endpoint.
- Cross-cutting concerns (locking, FSM, soft delete, RBAC) get dedicated tests, not just incidental coverage.

## Don't
- Don't test framework code (Spring MVC routing, JPA mechanics).
- Don't write tests that only assert mocks were called — assert observable behavior (returned value, persisted state, audit row written).
- Don't share mutable state across tests. Reset via `@BeforeEach` or use `@Transactional` rollback on integration tests.
- Don't load the full `@SpringBootTest` unless the slice tests are insufficient.
